00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:27.290
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
OK, any burning

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:33.480
issues from last time or
earlier, before I begin?

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:38.190
OK, we're going to do a little
primer on climate science

00:00:38.190 --> 00:00:41.160
and a very little primer
on the science and a primer

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:43.050
on the policy.

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:45.610
This could easily take
more than a semester.

00:00:45.610 --> 00:00:47.700
But we'll do it in
an hour and a half.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:55.960
So what I'm going to mostly do
is do what economists often do,

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:58.920
which is to say, well, let's
suppose we have a tsar.

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:02.940
Let's suppose we have a
tsar, who can set policy.

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:05.610
What would the tsar
do about climate?

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:11.310
Let's assume it's a modern
tsar, not a denyist tsar.

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:13.530
I'm going to argue
and try to indicate

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:17.790
to you why, even for a tsar,
this would be a hard problem.

00:01:17.790 --> 00:01:19.470
This is the hardest
public policy

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:23.010
problem I've ever come near.

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:26.850
So today, we have a tsar.

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:29.820
Wednesday and Friday, we don't.

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:31.110
It's like the real world.

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:34.890
And we will go through a
negotiation in which you

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.320
will be, as you know, on teams.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.210
We'll talk a little bit
about that at the end

00:01:39.210 --> 00:01:41.610
because we're going to have
to do some adjustments.

00:01:41.610 --> 00:01:43.230
You all want to
be rich countries.

00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:45.120
You can't all be rich countries.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:48.270
Some of you have to be poor.

00:01:48.270 --> 00:01:50.760
It's like life.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:55.740
All right, so let me do a
very little bit of background

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:58.200
on the science and then talk
about why it's a hard policy

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:00.660
problem.

00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:03.420
You've probably seen this graph.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:07.690
This is from NASA.

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:09.340
Global temperatures are rising.

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:12.670
If you look at the
last few years,

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:13.990
it looks like a slowdown.

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:16.120
This has been much debated.

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:17.950
The latest evidence
suggests this

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:21.830
is because of La Nina
conditions in the Pacific,

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:24.460
which tend to lower
the temperature.

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:30.190
And solar radiation is at
a minimum in its cycle.

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:32.410
Those who follow
these things closely

00:02:32.410 --> 00:02:35.890
expect, when we go to El Nino
conditions in the Pacific,

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.410
that we will break
previous records.

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:41.200
Nine of the 10 warmest
years on record

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:42.640
have been in this century.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:45.280
So if you smooth,
and you see there's

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:48.040
a lot of variability year
to year, if you smooth,

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:50.860
the trend is reasonably clear.

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.170
That's data.

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:54.980
This is inference.

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:58.180
There's strong evidence,
backed by theory,

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:01.250
that human activity has
a lot to do with this.

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:07.810
This is a global greenhouse
emissions by gas in 2004.

00:03:07.810 --> 00:03:12.940
You'll see, on the right,
CO2 from fossil fuel use

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:18.040
is a big contributor,
not the only contributor.

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:22.480
I think CO2 other is
probably cement manufacture.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:27.190
This is land use, deforestation,
biomass, agriculture,

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:28.930
and so forth.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:33.760
Methane, nitrous oxide, which
is a nasty, long-lived gas,

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.430
largely comes from agriculture.

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.350
Methane comes, of course,
from a variety of sources.

00:03:39.350 --> 00:03:41.200
And then there are a
bunch of long-lived,

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:46.040
very potent, but very small,
very low-concentration gases.

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:49.000
This is by sector.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.080
And again, you can see
an awful lot of this

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:57.130
is human activity obviously,
but generating electricity,

00:03:57.130 --> 00:03:59.620
manufacturing, transportation.

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:01.730
And again, you get
land use and forestry.

00:04:01.730 --> 00:04:03.250
So it's a range.

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:05.815
This is later data, but
it doesn't show it by gas.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:11.190
There are a wide variety
of activities involved

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:16.490
that emit heat-trapping gases.

00:04:16.490 --> 00:04:20.070
And again, there's
evidence, there's

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:23.340
theory that suggests that
this is really a driver.

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:27.240
The changes in solar
radiation, the El Nino, La Nina

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:29.370
is not big enough.

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:30.620
Yeah?

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:36.402
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] put the
carbon content [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:36.402 --> 00:04:37.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Largely.

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:40.310
You also lose soil carbon.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:44.990
If you cultivate and till
the soil, you'll lose.

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:47.780
You'll have an effect.

00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:49.550
You'll reduce what's
stored in the soil.

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:52.160
So it's mostly deforestation.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:55.730
But it can also be just
agricultural practices.

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:01.090
OK.

00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:03.700
But deforestation is crucial.

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:07.540
We're going to talk mostly
about CO2 from fossil fuels

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:09.820
because that's where
the policy action is

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:12.400
and also deforestation.

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:17.260
Mostly because you can
measure fossil fuel use

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.270
relatively easily.

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:22.360
Figuring out how agriculture
generates nitrous oxide

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:25.510
is harder, much
harder to measure.

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:28.810
But fuel use is relatively easy.

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:32.360
Deforestation is
relatively easy to measure.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:34.840
So you can actually
imagine agreements

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:36.530
that might be enforceable.

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.620
So that's where the
policy action is.

00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:40.990
We also know-- whoops.

00:05:40.990 --> 00:05:41.740
Back.

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:44.500
We also know that there
have been some clear impacts

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:45.540
of climate change.

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:47.200
This is everybody's seen this.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:51.580
This is the change in sea
ice since September of '79

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:53.830
to September of 2007.

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:56.260
And obviously, that continues.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:57.760
This is a projection.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:05:59.830
And it can only be a
projection, for reasons

00:05:59.830 --> 00:06:05.290
I want to talk about, of
days over 100 degrees.

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:09.950
And you see, gee, there,
it gets hot in the desert.

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:17.680
But the problem with this
is mainly human health.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:21.280
People who are fragile
in a variety of ways

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.260
or who aren't air
conditioned don't deal well

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:27.280
with large numbers of
days over 100 degrees.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:29.390
It happened in Europe
a couple of years ago.

00:06:29.390 --> 00:06:30.880
There were a number of--

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:35.110
more than a number, a
fair number of deaths.

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:37.570
So these are obvious impacts.

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:39.700
If it gets warmer, you
have more hot days.

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:42.670
If it gets warmer,
the sea ice melts.

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:47.350
But that's a small part
of the story is warming.

00:06:47.350 --> 00:06:50.713
So why is this hard?

00:06:50.713 --> 00:06:52.130
Why is this a hard
policy problem?

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:56.440
Step reason one is
the time scales.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:02.380
And the time scales, CO2 doesn't
come out of the atmosphere

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:04.610
by simple exponential decay.

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:06.070
The process is complicated.

00:07:06.070 --> 00:07:09.040
But if you think
about a half life,

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:13.060
you want to think about
around a century, if you can

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:15.730
think of it in half life terms.

00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:18.580
Not only does the stuff
stay up there a long time,

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:21.340
but it takes a long
time for its effects.

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:24.640
For the Earth to be in
equilibrium, depending

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:27.970
on how much heat is coming
in and being trapped,

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:30.520
you got to warm the deep ocean.

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:32.200
The deep ocean is deep.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:34.480
Heat diffuses slowly.

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:36.920
So it takes a while to warm.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.100
So we're not in equilibrium now.

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:41.860
And the question of how far
out of equilibrium we are

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:45.040
is kind of a serious one.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:48.190
So even if you cut
emissions sharply now,

00:07:48.190 --> 00:07:53.110
warming would
continue for decades.

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:56.350
Given that we're not going
to cut emissions sharply,

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:59.890
we're dealing with centuries.

00:07:59.890 --> 00:08:01.870
And in this literature,
people run out

00:08:01.870 --> 00:08:05.560
to 2100 and typically out
beyond 2100 in thinking

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:08.590
about a variety of things.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:13.040
Most human problems don't
have time scales like that.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:16.150
It means that
actions taken today

00:08:16.150 --> 00:08:19.340
will affect your grandchildren.

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:21.920
That's not true in
most areas of policy.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:24.830
You can do tax policy
lots between now

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:27.380
and the time your
grandchildren vote.

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:30.150
But CO2, it's still
going to be there.

00:08:30.150 --> 00:08:33.211
The CO2 emitted today will
still be there in large quantity

00:08:33.211 --> 00:08:34.669
when your grandchildren
are walking

00:08:34.669 --> 00:08:37.370
around blaming you for it.

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:42.530
So if we have a
climate tsar, he has

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:46.850
to think about how to
treat people not yet born

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:50.970
because actions today will
affect people not yet born.

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:53.000
I mean this is a
typical example.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.910
This is somebody's
story of what gets

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:59.000
flooded in Florida if you get
about a meter sea level rise.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.090
A meter sea level rise is
sort of order of magnitude

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:05.210
what might happen in a century.

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:13.700
What's it worth today
to prevent that in 2112?

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.330
For reference, my mother
lives there, more or less.

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:18.830
So she's OK.

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:20.480
On the other hand,
she's 90 years old.

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:22.940
This doesn't apply to her.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:27.930
But it will apply, potentially,
to great-great-grandchildren.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:32.090
So timescales of
a century or more

00:09:32.090 --> 00:09:38.300
are hard because you
know you want a discount.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:40.100
But how do you do that?

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:41.630
This is a live controversy.

00:09:41.630 --> 00:09:43.130
I'm not going to
give you an answer.

00:09:43.130 --> 00:09:45.920
Economists have nasty
arguments about this.

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:49.940
There are three ways you
might want to think about it.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:51.470
The obvious way to
think about, what

00:09:51.470 --> 00:09:53.270
am I going to do about
a century from now,

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:56.480
is to just think about
the private sector.

00:09:56.480 --> 00:09:59.270
Well, I could put it in a
bank, or I could invest it

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:00.890
in a business, or
I could invest it

00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:02.730
in dealing with climate change.

00:10:02.730 --> 00:10:04.440
I make that choice.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:08.060
So I ought to be using the
same kind of discounting

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:09.320
in both decisions, right?

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:12.650
Because I don't want
to have an imbalance.

00:10:12.650 --> 00:10:14.140
You missed the science.

00:10:14.140 --> 00:10:15.140
You could have fixed it.

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:20.990
This is Professor Solomon
who has forgotten more

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:24.860
about climate science than I
could ever aspire to learn.

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:26.790
At any rate, we're
talking about policy.

00:10:26.790 --> 00:10:29.210
And we're talking
about discounting

00:10:29.210 --> 00:10:31.940
and why this is hard.

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:37.250
So one school of
thought says, you've

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:41.580
got to use a private
sector discount rate.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:43.980
And one reason this
school of thought

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:48.180
achieved prominence was the
Army Corps of Engineers, when

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:51.120
deciding whether or
not to build dams,

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:54.240
always used a very
low discount rate.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:56.170
Dams last a long time.

00:10:56.170 --> 00:10:58.800
So if you use a very
low discount rate,

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:02.050
dams look pretty
promising economically.

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:05.892
And it was a huge slog
in the '50s and '60s

00:11:05.892 --> 00:11:08.100
to get the Corps of Engineers
to use a private sector

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:11.070
rate, to say, you can
build this kind of plant,

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:12.540
or you can build a dam.

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:15.480
You ought to use the same
discount rate in both cases.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.880
You ought to use the private
sector rate to think about

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:20.695
whether or not you build dams.

00:11:20.695 --> 00:11:22.570
There's a second school
of thought that says,

00:11:22.570 --> 00:11:23.153
wait a minute.

00:11:23.153 --> 00:11:27.180
This isn't really a
private sector decision.

00:11:27.180 --> 00:11:29.010
If you think about
optimal growth theory,

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:32.370
optimal growth
theory usually says--

00:11:32.370 --> 00:11:35.580
let me not do more than
wave my hands at that--

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:38.910
usually says there
are two reasons

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:40.980
you discount the future.

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:42.870
Forget the private
sector for the moment.

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:45.070
If you're doing everything
optimally in the economy,

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:46.987
there are two reasons
you discount the future.

00:11:46.987 --> 00:11:52.080
One, there might be a pure rate
of time preference, whatever

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:54.150
that might mean.

00:11:54.150 --> 00:11:58.620
And you value benefits in the
future less than benefits today

00:11:58.620 --> 00:12:01.320
because people in the
future will be richer.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:05.850
And, therefore-- being just
a little bit quick with

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:08.100
the hands--

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:11.180
income on the
margin's worth less.

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:14.130
If I were in the future
and I were richer,

00:12:14.130 --> 00:12:16.710
then $1 worth of benefit
would be worth less to me

00:12:16.710 --> 00:12:18.600
then than it is now.

00:12:18.600 --> 00:12:19.770
I'll take that into account.

00:12:19.770 --> 00:12:21.960
I'll discount that second
term because people

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:26.118
will be wealthier says,
you make a judgment.

00:12:26.118 --> 00:12:26.910
There are formulas.

00:12:26.910 --> 00:12:28.470
I won't trouble you.

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:32.050
There are formulas that say,
here's how you deal with that.

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:35.430
And then you say, well,
I have a preference.

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:37.950
We all have preference
for today over tomorrow.

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:40.950
That's a pure rate
of time preference.

00:12:40.950 --> 00:12:45.030
The third approach that's
coming into the literature

00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:47.820
recently says, why do you have
a pure rate of time preference?

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:49.380
What does that mean?

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:52.850
That discriminates
between generations.

00:12:52.850 --> 00:12:56.080
The pure rate of time preference
says, even if my grandchildren

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:00.270
are no richer than
I am, I'm going

00:13:00.270 --> 00:13:04.220
to value $1 to them
less than $1 to me.

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:07.900
That doesn't make moral sense.

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:11.280
So I would use a zero rate
of pure time preference

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:15.540
and then make a judgment, if I
want to, about how much richer

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:17.790
they will be and how
much that ought to matter

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:20.460
when I think about benefits.

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:24.990
Now, I present this not--

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:28.080
those are very
different positions.

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:29.940
And they have very
different implications

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:31.750
for how you think
about the future.

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:33.690
And I have to tell
you, depending

00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:37.710
on the day of the week and the
weather, I myself vacillate.

00:13:37.710 --> 00:13:42.790
But let me just give
you the implications.

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:46.350
Let's take rates to
illustrate these.

00:13:46.350 --> 00:13:51.930
7% and 3% are used in federal
government decision making.

00:13:51.930 --> 00:13:55.730
The 7%, you might think of as
like a private sector rate.

00:13:55.730 --> 00:14:00.750
The 3% gets down to that second
category, the pure rate of time

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:02.940
preference plus an adjustment.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:09.810
And 1% was used in an
influential report on climate

00:14:09.810 --> 00:14:13.920
change that takes the third
position, no pure rate of time

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:18.360
preference, no discrimination
between generations.

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:24.430
So let's apply that to
$1 million in 100 years.

00:14:24.430 --> 00:14:27.670
All right, if I use 1%,
that $1 million in 100 years

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:30.430
is worth $368,000.

00:14:30.430 --> 00:14:32.410
So I'd spend a fair amount.

00:14:32.410 --> 00:14:34.300
I wouldn't spend
$1 million today.

00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:36.352
But I'd spend a fair
amount to avoid a 1 million

00:14:36.352 --> 00:14:37.435
dollar's worth of damages.

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:43.480
3%, woo.

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:45.370
I wouldn't spend
very much at all

00:14:45.370 --> 00:14:49.150
to avoid 1 million
dollar's worth of damages.

00:14:49.150 --> 00:14:53.440
And at 7%, we get what a
guy who used to work for me

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:56.320
called the magic ray gun.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:01.690
You let me discount anything at
7% in the future, it goes away.

00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:06.190
It's a disappearing function.

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:10.120
I would spend $9,000 today to
avoid 1 million dollar's worth

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:13.900
of damages in 100 years if
I use that discount rate.

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:16.160
It matters a lot.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:18.650
It matters a lot.

00:15:18.650 --> 00:15:21.640
And there's no
easy way to decide,

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:24.670
I think, to decide
among these views.

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:27.955
If you scratch most economists,
they come down here at 3%.

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:32.830
But if you ask them,
well, wait a minute.

00:15:32.830 --> 00:15:34.790
Aren't you crowding out
private investments?

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:36.040
They say, oh, well, maybe.

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:37.780
Maybe not.

00:15:37.780 --> 00:15:40.240
And if you ask them, well,
why are you discriminating

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:42.880
against future generations
with this pure rate of time

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:44.080
preference?

00:15:44.080 --> 00:15:47.500
Where does that come from?

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:50.770
Most people go, well,
yeah, that's a point.

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:54.040
So you can make arguments
for all three of these.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:55.870
And they have very
different implications.

00:15:55.870 --> 00:15:58.990
The tsar will have to choose.

00:15:58.990 --> 00:15:59.830
See the issue?

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:01.390
I hope.

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:03.670
If you're talking about
five years, 10 years,

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:05.110
it doesn't matter that much.

00:16:05.110 --> 00:16:07.540
If you're talking about 100
years, which we are here,

00:16:07.540 --> 00:16:11.380
it does, or more.

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:15.760
OK, that's hard.

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:17.200
And it's hard for the tsar.

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:18.987
It's not just hard politically.

00:16:22.090 --> 00:16:24.400
So that's one reason
why it's hard.

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:28.000
The tsar is willing to
make sacrifices today

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.160
for generations not yet
born or even thought of.

00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:36.250
Many other people, who aren't
as farsighted as the tsar,

00:16:36.250 --> 00:16:39.730
may have trouble doing
that or voting to do that.

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:42.370
That's a tough trade off, right?

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:45.460
We could reduce
emissions today sharply,

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:47.800
and it wouldn't make
much difference to us,

00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:50.050
might not make much
difference to us,

00:16:50.050 --> 00:16:52.300
might make some difference
to our children,

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:54.353
might make a lot of
difference to their children.

00:16:54.353 --> 00:16:56.770
You can't even imagine having
grandchildren at this point,

00:16:56.770 --> 00:16:57.100
right?

00:16:57.100 --> 00:16:57.600
All right?

00:16:57.600 --> 00:17:00.280
I hope.

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:02.870
But you will.

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:04.900
And so will they.

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:06.640
OK, that's one
reason why it's hard

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:08.829
because it's hard to think
in terms of a century

00:17:08.829 --> 00:17:13.520
when you're making
decisions today or more.

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:15.940
A second reason why this
is hard even for the tsar

00:17:15.940 --> 00:17:19.534
is uncertainty.

00:17:19.534 --> 00:17:26.609
And one of the things Professor
Solomon and I have learned

00:17:26.609 --> 00:17:29.940
is you can't say uncertain
in public discourse.

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:32.280
Because uncertain to the
public means, my god,

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:34.110
I don't have a clue.

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:36.960
What uncertain means
in this context is,

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:39.060
I may not know the
probability distribution.

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:42.130
But there is a
probability distribution.

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:43.050
It's not oh my.

00:17:43.050 --> 00:17:47.910
And it's not
infinitely spread out.

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:51.480
If you think about
elements of uncertainty,

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:53.790
what will the atmosphere
look like in 100 years

00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:55.650
if we don't do anything?

00:17:55.650 --> 00:17:58.770
Well, you know, that
depends on population.

00:17:58.770 --> 00:17:59.820
Does China collapse?

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:00.870
Does China not collapse?

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:02.910
It depends on future
economic growth.

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:04.650
It depends on the
mix of activity.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.140
What happens to manufacturing
versus services?

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:09.930
It depends on new technologies.

00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:11.940
Somebody comes up
with cheap storage.

00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:13.470
The world moves to solar power.

00:18:13.470 --> 00:18:18.280
It's a very different world
than if that doesn't happen.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:20.030
Those are all big uncertainties.

00:18:20.030 --> 00:18:22.470
So we don't really know what
emissions will look like.

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:28.290
There are uncertainties
about the climate system,

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:30.480
serious uncertainties
about the climate system,

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:32.670
not that we don't know anything.

00:18:32.670 --> 00:18:34.920
But as I mentioned,
there's this issue of,

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:38.010
how fast will the
deep ocean warm?

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:40.920
There are issues of
irreversibility and tipping

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:42.150
points, potentially.

00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:44.670
Did you want to talk about
that and say a word about some

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:46.620
of these uncertainties?

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:48.090
Can I provoke you
into a comment?

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:53.880
SUSAN SOLOMON: Possibly.

00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:56.213
I guess I'm not quite sure
where you want to go with it.

00:18:56.213 --> 00:19:00.720
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Oh, I just
want some illustrative detail

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:05.010
or some examples of things
that might be a concern

00:19:05.010 --> 00:19:07.470
or that might be
nonlinearities or that might

00:19:07.470 --> 00:19:09.850
be like falling off a table.

00:19:09.850 --> 00:19:10.600
SUSAN SOLOMON: OK.

00:19:13.442 --> 00:19:15.400
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You
want to take a second?

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:17.680
Just take a second.

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:19.600
I hate to waste the resource.

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:22.120
SUSAN SOLOMON: I'll do my best.

00:19:22.120 --> 00:19:24.250
This issue of tipping
points, in my mind,

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:26.880
is actually a lot more
difficult than the issue

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:28.510
of irreversibility.

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:32.140
The irreversibility problem,
we can talk about a little bit

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:34.180
more clearly.

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:40.690
For example, if it were to
be the case that Arctic sea

00:19:40.690 --> 00:19:45.610
ice were to disappear,
you might imagine

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:49.840
that that would be an
irreversible process.

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:51.610
But I think we're
finding, more and more,

00:19:51.610 --> 00:19:53.920
that it actually isn't.

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:56.890
Even though we had very
low Arctic sea ice in 2007,

00:19:56.890 --> 00:19:59.290
because we have
such cold winters,

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:03.640
we have the ability to reform
the sea ice because it's thin.

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:05.680
Even when you have
multiyear ice,

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:07.060
it's still relatively thin.

00:20:07.060 --> 00:20:09.370
It's only a few
years that matters.

00:20:09.370 --> 00:20:12.370
But when we, for
example, do something

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:14.860
that causes a big dent in
the Greenland ice sheet,

00:20:14.860 --> 00:20:17.950
now that truly is
something that you could

00:20:17.950 --> 00:20:21.430
think about as irreversible.

00:20:21.430 --> 00:20:23.790
It's going to take a
very, very long time.

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:26.560
So on human timescales, it's
essentially irreversible

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:30.160
if you lose a big piece of
the Greenland ice sheet.

00:20:30.160 --> 00:20:33.820
Is there a tipping point
beyond which the Greenland ice

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:36.970
sheet might kind of
suddenly fall apart

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:39.580
is something that's been raised.

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:41.920
Much more of a
controversial issue.

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:43.870
It's conceivable.

00:20:43.870 --> 00:20:47.500
But most scientists
who study the ice

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:51.340
would argue that it's more
likely to be a slow process.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:52.550
But it's possible.

00:20:52.550 --> 00:20:56.950
And one of the
things that could be

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:59.860
a tipping point for the
Arctic, that people have also

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:02.890
talked about, of course,
is methane release

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:08.920
from things like undersea
deposits of methane

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:14.080
that are actually tied up in
formations called clathrates

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:16.480
and also in permafrost,
which you're probably

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:17.660
more familiar with.

00:21:17.660 --> 00:21:20.980
So there are ways
to trigger things

00:21:20.980 --> 00:21:25.210
that, in the tipping point
framework, usually involve ice.

00:21:25.210 --> 00:21:27.070
And you can sort of
see why that would be.

00:21:27.070 --> 00:21:28.540
It's either ice, or it's not.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:34.490
There is slow transition
from one to another.

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:36.450
It's a real change of state.

00:21:36.450 --> 00:21:37.325
So that's some ideas.

00:21:37.325 --> 00:21:38.325
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK.

00:21:38.325 --> 00:21:39.130
Thank you.

00:21:39.130 --> 00:21:40.330
Thank you.

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:43.960
So that's hard.

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:48.430
The tsar has to think about
those possibilities, which

00:21:48.430 --> 00:21:49.910
we know something.

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:51.010
But we don't know.

00:21:51.010 --> 00:21:52.540
We can't tell when
that might occur,

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:56.040
if those things might occur.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:02.100
Even climate models,
complex simulation models

00:22:02.100 --> 00:22:03.450
of the climate system--

00:22:03.450 --> 00:22:05.700
and there are a number of them--

00:22:05.700 --> 00:22:09.520
disagree on what
happens regionally.

00:22:09.520 --> 00:22:12.360
Will it be wetter or drier?

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:15.310
Well, that matters a lot.

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:18.240
It matters a lot whether
it'll be wetter or drier

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:19.380
in particular areas.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:23.310
Well, let me just say that.

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:25.680
Also, we don't have
good predictions

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:33.090
for the impacts on hurricanes,
more, more intense,

00:22:33.090 --> 00:22:34.650
none of the above.

00:22:34.650 --> 00:22:36.840
More water goes into the
air because it's warmer.

00:22:36.840 --> 00:22:37.483
It comes down.

00:22:37.483 --> 00:22:38.400
How does it come down?

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:40.680
Where does it come down?

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:44.550
Very uncertain implications
for regional impacts.

00:22:48.300 --> 00:22:52.000
Regional impacts will
take us into new ground,

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:55.290
particularly for ecosystems.

00:22:55.290 --> 00:22:59.670
We don't quite know how
ecosystems will respond

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.200
because we haven't done it.

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:04.020
It's not an easy experiment.

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:08.970
So damages, effects like
rainfall are uncertain.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:14.550
The implications of those
effects are also uncertain.

00:23:14.550 --> 00:23:19.380
And finally, there's
little experience

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:22.380
in sort of, how do human
civilizations react

00:23:22.380 --> 00:23:26.250
to large-scale environmental
changes of various kinds?

00:23:26.250 --> 00:23:28.170
I've been seeing, on
Google News, reference

00:23:28.170 --> 00:23:30.810
to small changes
in rainfall being

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:33.390
the likely culprit in the
downfall of the Mayans,

00:23:33.390 --> 00:23:37.800
maybe 20%, 30% reductions,
not huge droughts.

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:39.910
Sensitive enough.

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:42.310
Are poor countries in the
tropics that sensitive?

00:23:42.310 --> 00:23:43.030
Probably not.

00:23:43.030 --> 00:23:45.850
How sensitive?

00:23:45.850 --> 00:23:48.370
All right, finally, the
cost of emissions reductions

00:23:48.370 --> 00:23:50.510
are also uncertain.

00:23:50.510 --> 00:23:52.630
So the tsar is going to
have to deal with this.

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:55.420
And the tsar is going to
have to deal with the fact

00:23:55.420 --> 00:23:57.920
that we will be
learning as we go.

00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:02.288
So this is I now go to my
favorite picture from the--

00:24:02.288 --> 00:24:04.330
so you can't do cost
benefit analysis because you

00:24:04.330 --> 00:24:05.163
don't know the cost.

00:24:05.163 --> 00:24:08.210
And you don't know the benefits.

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:10.750
So the tsar can't
just do the arithmetic

00:24:10.750 --> 00:24:13.570
because he doesn't know
the cost or the benefits,

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:16.180
even if he could
do the discounting.

00:24:16.180 --> 00:24:20.410
A problem like this needs
adaptive or iterative risk

00:24:20.410 --> 00:24:21.610
management.

00:24:21.610 --> 00:24:25.270
And you can read that in
the report of the Committee

00:24:25.270 --> 00:24:28.450
on America's Climate Choices,
on which Professor Solomon and I

00:24:28.450 --> 00:24:30.280
both served.

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:34.210
If you think about steering a
ship in iceberg-infested waters

00:24:34.210 --> 00:24:41.490
at night before radar,
to avoid the Titanic,

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:44.400
the elements of what a
sensible skipper does

00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:46.470
are the elements of
what the tsar would

00:24:46.470 --> 00:24:48.510
do to deal with climate.

00:24:48.510 --> 00:24:50.370
You slow down.

00:24:50.370 --> 00:24:51.220
Good plan.

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:54.290
So you reduce emissions.

00:24:54.290 --> 00:24:56.840
You don't quite know
what the consequences

00:24:56.840 --> 00:25:01.070
are of having more emissions
or of going faster.

00:25:01.070 --> 00:25:03.740
But you know they're
probably not good on balance.

00:25:03.740 --> 00:25:05.420
So you slow down.

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:09.410
You prepare for
something to happen.

00:25:09.410 --> 00:25:12.930
You prepare to adapt.

00:25:12.930 --> 00:25:14.100
You learn.

00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:15.420
You station lookouts.

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:16.590
You study the system.

00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:19.140
You see what's going on.

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:23.610
You develop options, new
technologies, geoengineering,

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:25.710
which I'll talk about briefly.

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:28.920
And you try to figure
out a system that enables

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:31.690
learning to affect decisions.

00:25:31.690 --> 00:25:35.280
So you want to hear the lookouts
when they see something.

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:37.560
So that's the sort
of thing the tsar

00:25:37.560 --> 00:25:42.920
is going to have to do because
we don't know probabilities.

00:25:42.920 --> 00:25:46.442
We don't know, really,
models and studies

00:25:46.442 --> 00:25:48.650
of what's going to happen
to the Greenland ice sheet.

00:25:48.650 --> 00:25:51.840
But we don't know for sure.

00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:53.245
We don't know for sure.

00:25:53.245 --> 00:25:54.870
And we don't know
for sure whether it's

00:25:54.870 --> 00:25:56.685
going to get wetter
or drier in Ethiopia.

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:04.830
So just a word about
adaptation, the tsar

00:26:04.830 --> 00:26:08.250
will have to have
to do some of this.

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:11.020
But as I said, the small scale--

00:26:11.020 --> 00:26:13.170
and we will adapt.

00:26:13.170 --> 00:26:16.260
That first line is one
of my favorite statements

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:19.560
about adaptation, which is,
the default mode of adaptation

00:26:19.560 --> 00:26:21.290
is suffering.

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:22.400
So we'll adapt.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:26.720
But the question is, will
we actually do any changes?

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:31.430
Will we do any
proactive adaptation?

00:26:31.430 --> 00:26:34.790
As I said, problem one is that
the climate models differ.

00:26:34.790 --> 00:26:36.450
And I will give you an example.

00:26:36.450 --> 00:26:39.380
A colleague was called in by
the government of Ethiopia

00:26:39.380 --> 00:26:40.440
some years ago.

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:42.890
And they said, all
right, we believe there's

00:26:42.890 --> 00:26:44.370
going to be climate change.

00:26:44.370 --> 00:26:46.040
What do we do?

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:49.980
Half the climate models say
it's going to get drier.

00:26:49.980 --> 00:26:53.780
And half the climate models
say it's going to get wetter.

00:26:53.780 --> 00:27:00.410
How exactly do we prepare
for this uncertain future?

00:27:00.410 --> 00:27:04.300
Their answer was pave the roads.

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:07.960
Because if it's drier,
OK, you have paved roads.

00:27:07.960 --> 00:27:11.620
If it's wetter, a problem that
Ethiopia traditionally has

00:27:11.620 --> 00:27:15.250
is that unpaved roads wash out
when there's heavy rainfall.

00:27:15.250 --> 00:27:19.610
And the whole process of getting
food to market breaks down.

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:23.800
So if it gets wetter, you
will really need paved roads.

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:26.170
And if it doesn't get
wetter, paved roads

00:27:26.170 --> 00:27:28.853
are not a bad thing to have.

00:27:28.853 --> 00:27:30.520
There are going to
be a lot of decisions

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:34.310
like that, a lot of people
looking for robust policies.

00:27:34.310 --> 00:27:37.270
The second problem, of course,
is the tsar can't possibly

00:27:37.270 --> 00:27:39.530
make all these decisions.

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:42.270
They're going to be made
at state and local levels.

00:27:42.270 --> 00:27:46.640
A number of cities and states
have now, already in the US

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:48.860
and certainly foreign
countries, have now

00:27:48.860 --> 00:27:52.790
processes in place to think
about this, to try to think

00:27:52.790 --> 00:27:55.310
about things as Ethiopia did.

00:27:55.310 --> 00:27:57.900
What can we do that's robust?

00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:03.150
If we're going to have sea level
rise, how do we cope with that?

00:28:03.150 --> 00:28:04.920
What do we need to
do about hurricanes?

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:07.440
How do we change
various policies?

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:09.660
An awful lot of that is local.

00:28:09.660 --> 00:28:11.355
Awful lot of that
has to be local.

00:28:11.355 --> 00:28:15.260
An awful lot of that's going
to be in poor countries.

00:28:15.260 --> 00:28:18.230
So adaptation will happen.

00:28:18.230 --> 00:28:20.480
The tsar will try to do
something about that.

00:28:20.480 --> 00:28:23.240
