00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:01.950
to a little pseudo-science.

00:40:01.950 --> 00:40:08.070
Suppose you want to
reduce emissions.

00:40:08.070 --> 00:40:11.820
Say you want a total
reduction in emissions

00:40:11.820 --> 00:40:15.540
from business as
usual of capital R.

00:40:15.540 --> 00:40:17.160
And you want to do it worldwide.

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:20.070
And the cost of getting
reductions in country I

00:40:20.070 --> 00:40:22.620
is given by this cost function.

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:26.560
All right, so the tsar
cares about global cost.

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:29.910
So what the tsar is going
to do is reduce emissions.

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:33.330
He's going to minimize
the total cost

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:36.940
subject to this constraint.

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:41.820
And if you recall or
just use your intuition,

00:40:41.820 --> 00:40:44.730
you're going to have to have the
marginal cost, the derivative

00:40:44.730 --> 00:40:47.280
of this function with
respect to its argument

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:50.010
equal across countries.

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:53.330
If not, I can
rearrange reductions

00:40:53.330 --> 00:40:55.280
in a way that will lower costs.

00:40:55.280 --> 00:40:57.470
I'll do a little more
where marginal cost is

00:40:57.470 --> 00:40:59.780
low and a little less where
marginal cost is high.

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:02.240
Get the same
reductions, lower cost.

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:06.050
That's always true unless
the marginal costs are equal.

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:08.510
Well, if marginal
costs are going

00:41:08.510 --> 00:41:14.990
to be equal, then unless it's
really hard to reduce emissions

00:41:14.990 --> 00:41:17.450
in poor countries, they
have to play if we're

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:19.850
going to reduce total cost.

