It's not a question
of who pays for it.

00:41:23.150 --> 00:41:26.700
It's a question of
where it happens, right?

00:41:26.700 --> 00:41:31.050
Doesn't say that that Bangladesh
has to pay to reduce emissions

00:41:31.050 --> 00:41:32.340
in Bangladesh.

00:41:32.340 --> 00:41:35.070
It says that emissions
in Bangladesh

00:41:35.070 --> 00:41:37.620
will have to be reduced.

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:39.380
So they're separate questions.

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:41.450
But it says the poor
will need to be involved.

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:50.450
If you recall 1401, if
you have a firm producing

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:55.190
in multiple plants, this is
exactly the same principle.

00:41:55.190 --> 00:41:56.935
You want to equalize
on the margin.

00:41:59.810 --> 00:42:03.730
Normally, it means
everybody has to play.

00:42:03.730 --> 00:42:06.440
There are two
approaches that have

00:42:06.440 --> 00:42:07.940
been put on the table for this.

00:42:07.940 --> 00:42:11.330
And we'll come back
to both of them.

00:42:11.330 --> 00:42:14.150
The Parsons, et al,
piece on the reading

00:42:14.150 --> 00:42:18.800
list, which is optional,
talks about one of them.

00:42:18.800 --> 00:42:26.720
You could say, all right,
how about the tsar says

00:42:26.720 --> 00:42:29.570
there's a price of
$20 a ton for carbon

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:33.150
emissions from fossil fuels?

00:42:33.150 --> 00:42:37.010
The tsar doesn't like
to do central planning.

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:39.200
He's learned that lesson.

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:40.880
But the tsar can
tinker with prices.

00:42:40.880 --> 00:42:45.690
So he'll put a price of
$20 a ton for emissions.

00:42:45.690 --> 00:42:49.860
Well, that means everybody
who's contemplating emissions

00:42:49.860 --> 00:42:54.330
is going to cut back until
the cost of cutting back rises

00:42:54.330 --> 00:42:56.410
to $20.

00:42:56.410 --> 00:43:01.700
And I'll get this marginal
cost of quality that way.

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:03.670
All right, so I'll
just price the thing.

00:43:03.670 --> 00:43:05.060
We talked about this earlier.

00:43:05.060 --> 00:43:07.100
This is pricing the harm.

00:43:07.100 --> 00:43:08.050
So I priced the harm.

00:43:08.050 --> 00:43:10.840
People cut back on the harm.

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:11.740
It's a tax.

00:43:11.740 --> 00:43:16.420
It'll show up as a tax, probably
show up as a tax on fuel.

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:18.823
Tax much higher on coal
than on natural gas.

00:43:18.823 --> 00:43:19.990
But that's one way to do it.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:23.000
And the tsar can do that.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.820
The other way to do it--

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:26.820
that makes sense, right?

00:43:26.820 --> 00:43:27.890
That's easy?

00:43:27.890 --> 00:43:28.890
We just price the thing.

00:43:31.750 --> 00:43:35.077
The other way to do it is a
little more convoluted but only

00:43:35.077 --> 00:43:35.660
a little more.

00:43:35.660 --> 00:43:37.118
And we'll return
to the equivalence

00:43:37.118 --> 00:43:44.370
later on is the tsar prints
up certificates, drops

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:51.380
from helicopters, and
says, to emit a ton of CO2,

00:43:51.380 --> 00:43:55.560
you have to give
me a certificate.

00:43:55.560 --> 00:43:58.580
Limited number of certificates
equal to the total amount

00:43:58.580 --> 00:44:04.670
of CO2 the tsar wants to
permit, you get a market, right?

00:44:04.670 --> 00:44:06.410
I go around looking
for certificates.

00:44:06.410 --> 00:44:08.040
I'm willing to pay
20 bucks for it.

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:10.260
I'm willing to pay some price.

00:44:10.260 --> 00:44:12.630
The market will
determine what price.

00:44:12.630 --> 00:44:15.570
In this case, if I fix
a price, the market

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:17.760
will determine the quantity.

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:21.480
If I fix a quantity, the market
will determine the price.

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:24.850
But I can go either way.

00:44:24.850 --> 00:44:26.430
And if the tsar
knows all, it doesn't

00:44:26.430 --> 00:44:29.040
matter which way he goes.

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:30.930
We'll talk a little
later, I think,

00:44:30.930 --> 00:44:34.060
about when and where
and how it might matter.

00:44:34.060 --> 00:44:39.796
But that's what the
tsar might want to do.

00:44:39.796 --> 00:44:43.630
But do those make sort
of top of the head sense

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:50.130
as a way to do it without having
to do central planning for all

00:44:50.130 --> 00:44:52.900
the nations of the world?

00:44:52.900 --> 00:44:57.060
But if you say it's
$30 a ton or $40 a ton

00:44:57.060 --> 00:45:02.040
for everybody and poor
countries have to pay it,

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:04.030
how do they do that?

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:06.770
How do they do that?

00:45:06.770 --> 00:45:11.900
So you know that they're going
to have to do some reduction.

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:17.080
Because if you think
about it, they're

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:20.590
building buildings,
facilities, et cetera.

00:45:20.590 --> 00:45:24.980
It's a lot cheaper to
insulate a new house

00:45:24.980 --> 00:45:31.160
when it's being built than to go
back and retrofit an old house.

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:34.220
It's a lot cheaper to make
a new power plant efficient

00:45:34.220 --> 00:45:37.660
than to repower an
old power plant.

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:41.020
So if the poorer
countries of the world

00:45:41.020 --> 00:45:43.960
are growing more
rapidly, they have

00:45:43.960 --> 00:45:47.050
a lot more relatively
inexpensive investment

00:45:47.050 --> 00:45:49.920
opportunities.

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:52.800
They also may not have
built Los Angeles yet.

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:55.830
So they're in a position
to decide more easily

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:59.520
on a different urban
structure, less spread out,

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:00.930
less reliant on cars.

00:46:00.930 --> 00:46:05.280
So there are a set of
choices that are being made.

00:46:05.280 --> 00:46:08.740
There are also, if you
look at retrofit options,

00:46:08.740 --> 00:46:14.760
there's a lot of energy use
now that is polluting as well

00:46:14.760 --> 00:46:17.230
as inefficient.

00:46:17.230 --> 00:46:22.470
So modernizing some
of the plants now

00:46:22.470 --> 00:46:25.780
will create a double benefit.

00:46:25.780 --> 00:46:28.780
If you can do something besides
little kerosene generators,

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:31.330
for instance, for electricity
in a lot of places,

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:35.110
you will not only save
energy, but you clean the air.

00:46:35.110 --> 00:46:38.890
So there's a benefit
to be had in bringing

00:46:38.890 --> 00:46:46.420
these countries closer to the
frontier with what they already

00:46:46.420 --> 00:46:47.750
have.

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:48.250
OK.

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:56.630
So this is a hard
problem for the tsar.

00:46:56.630 --> 00:47:00.620
The tsar has to figure
out how she's going to--

00:47:00.620 --> 00:47:02.270
or the tsarina, how
she's going to deal

00:47:02.270 --> 00:47:07.560
with the distant future and
great-great-grandchildren,

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:12.450
how to deal with
uncertainty today

00:47:12.450 --> 00:47:17.730
and to learn to deal with a
tomorrow as learning happens.

00:47:17.730 --> 00:47:21.210
The tsar is going to have to
figure out what, if anything,

00:47:21.210 --> 00:47:24.120
could be done about
technologies, how to get people

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:27.300
and able to adapt.

00:47:27.300 --> 00:47:30.990
If the tsar focuses
on fossil fuel,

00:47:30.990 --> 00:47:33.810
the tsar has to
make big changes.

00:47:33.810 --> 00:47:37.420
And the tsar has to
involve the poor.

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:39.250
The tsar has to
involve the poor.

00:47:39.250 --> 00:47:42.070
It can't be done
by rich countries.

00:47:42.070 --> 00:47:44.060
If rich countries
alone try to do it,

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:48.400
if you go back to something like
this, you want to slow growth.

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:50.890
You want to eliminate
growth in emissions

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:53.290
by only the rich
countries, they'd

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:56.120
have to go to zero
to have a big impact.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:47:57.650
It isn't going to happen.

00:47:57.650 --> 00:48:01.320
So the pole need to be involved.

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:06.930
And the first question that
comes up, already came up,

00:48:06.930 --> 00:48:07.615
is that fair?

00:48:11.140 --> 00:48:14.090
This is emissions per capita.

00:48:14.090 --> 00:48:18.500
This is Annex II North
America is US and Canada.

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:22.620
This is Australia,
New Zealand, Japan.

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:26.100
EIT, or Economies In
Transition, that's

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:28.200
Russia and Eastern Europe.

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:29.790
There's the Middle East.

00:48:29.790 --> 00:48:33.900
Annex II Europe or rich
European countries,

00:48:33.900 --> 00:48:37.755
China, other countries, Latin
America, the rest of Asia,

00:48:37.755 --> 00:48:38.255
Africa.

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:45.710
Is it fair to involve them?

00:48:45.710 --> 00:48:47.360
My golly.

00:48:47.360 --> 00:48:49.520
You're going to go to Cambodia.

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:53.060
You remember I put up the
Cambodia energy diagram

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:54.260
some while ago.

00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:58.390
Cambodia imports some oil
and burns a lot of wood.

00:48:58.390 --> 00:48:59.670
That's the energy system.

00:49:02.950 --> 00:49:05.020
And they mostly ride motorbikes.

00:49:05.020 --> 00:49:08.350
And you can't get them
much smaller than the ones

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:09.090
they have.

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:14.870
So this is an enormous
disparity, right?

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:16.300
North America is running--

00:49:16.300 --> 00:49:17.320
I don't know--

00:49:17.320 --> 00:49:19.970
16 metric tons per capita.

00:49:19.970 --> 00:49:23.200
Africa is running less than one.

00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:23.980
Big disparity.

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:24.910
Huge disparity.

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:25.930
Very different.

00:49:25.930 --> 00:49:27.250
Very different systems.

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:29.590
So if you're going
to change, you're

00:49:29.590 --> 00:49:31.030
going to look
people in the face.

00:49:31.030 --> 00:49:33.640
And those of you who want
to be developing countries

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:36.550
or developed countries
on Wednesday and Friday

00:49:36.550 --> 00:49:39.970
are going to look your poor
brethren in the face and say,

00:49:39.970 --> 00:49:43.300
you, Latin America,
rest of Asia, Africa,

00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:45.560
boy, you've got to take steps.

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:47.930
We'll do what we can.

00:49:47.930 --> 00:49:49.580
But you've got to take steps.

00:49:49.580 --> 00:49:52.760
Say, we have path
dependence up here.

00:49:52.760 --> 00:49:54.315
We're kind of stuck on a path.

00:49:54.315 --> 00:49:55.940
And you know, what
are you going to do?

00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:04.400
So fairness is also in one
response might be, yeah, well,

00:50:04.400 --> 00:50:07.280
let's look not per capita.

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:12.457
But you're low because
you're really, really poor.

00:50:12.457 --> 00:50:14.040
And we're really,
really sad about it.

00:50:14.040 --> 00:50:19.890
But per dollar of GDP, the
differences are less stark.

00:50:19.890 --> 00:50:24.120
The winners now are the
Middle East, Soviet Union,

00:50:24.120 --> 00:50:27.990
and Eastern Europe
because those were really

00:50:27.990 --> 00:50:30.570
manufacturing-intensive
technologies.

00:50:30.570 --> 00:50:34.220
They ran on cheap
Russian oil, which

00:50:34.220 --> 00:50:38.360
was made available at low
cost, and Russian natural gas.

00:50:38.360 --> 00:50:41.090
They still have an anomalous
amount of inefficient capital

00:50:41.090 --> 00:50:44.240
stock running.

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:47.240
And China, which has a
manufacturing-intensive economy

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:48.350
and uses a lot of coal.

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:55.120
So per unit of GDP, Africa is
right in there with everybody

00:50:55.120 --> 00:50:56.320
else.

00:50:56.320 --> 00:50:59.960
They just happen to have
not much GDP per capita.

00:50:59.960 --> 00:51:03.850
So you say, well, per dollar
of GDP, we can make cuts.

00:51:03.850 --> 00:51:06.480
You can make cuts.

00:51:06.480 --> 00:51:10.530
And one response might be, yeah,
but we'd like our GDP to grow.

00:51:10.530 --> 00:51:13.510
Thank you very much.

