OK.

00:52:12.630 --> 00:52:16.980
A little bit of sort of how
the international conversation

00:52:16.980 --> 00:52:21.680
on all of this has gone,
just by way of background,

00:52:21.680 --> 00:52:23.430
and then we'll see
what questions you have

00:52:23.430 --> 00:52:27.360
because I've gone through
this much too rapidly.

00:52:27.360 --> 00:52:31.320
As I mentioned, the Framework
Convention on Climate Change

00:52:31.320 --> 00:52:38.050
was drafted in 1992,
ratified by everybody.

00:52:38.050 --> 00:52:41.350
There have been 17 conferences
of the parties referred

00:52:41.350 --> 00:52:46.690
to as COPs, large
gatherings of diplomats,

00:52:46.690 --> 00:52:53.410
nongovernmental organizations,
demonstrators, hangers on,

00:52:53.410 --> 00:52:56.500
cocktail parties, receptions.

00:52:56.500 --> 00:52:59.720
There have been 17 of them.

00:52:59.720 --> 00:53:00.740
You will be the 18th.

00:53:03.260 --> 00:53:06.880
The third produced
the Kyoto Protocol.

00:53:06.880 --> 00:53:11.230
The Framework Convention
divided the world

00:53:11.230 --> 00:53:14.530
into Annex I countries
and everybody else.

00:53:14.530 --> 00:53:17.680
Annex II, which was on some
of those earlier graphs,

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:23.560
is a subset of Annex I. It's
the richer Annex I countries.

00:53:23.560 --> 00:53:32.200
The Kyoto Protocol called
for Annex I countries only.

00:53:32.200 --> 00:53:34.480
And by the way, it's
not all rich countries.

00:53:34.480 --> 00:53:38.140
South Korea is not
Annex I. Singapore

00:53:38.140 --> 00:53:42.680
is not Annex I. Saudi Arabia
is not Annex I and so forth.

00:53:42.680 --> 00:53:45.433
So it's industrialized
countries.

00:53:45.433 --> 00:53:49.250
OECD, roughly, OECD.

00:53:49.250 --> 00:53:53.540
Annex I countries were
to make reductions that

00:53:53.540 --> 00:53:55.640
were negotiated reductions.

00:53:55.640 --> 00:53:58.640
The rest of the
world, which I just

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:02.270
said has to participate if
something's going to happen,

00:54:02.270 --> 00:54:07.180
refused to even promise
making promises in the future.

00:54:07.180 --> 00:54:09.450
So there wasn't
even a commitment

00:54:09.450 --> 00:54:11.340
to make a commitment.

00:54:11.340 --> 00:54:14.210
They would not commit to commit.

00:54:14.210 --> 00:54:18.120
And if you think about that,
that's really resisting.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:19.890
We'll be happy to come
to these meetings.

00:54:19.890 --> 00:54:24.060
But we do not now promise
ever to commit to do anything,

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:25.960
unless, of course,
it's paid for.

00:54:25.960 --> 00:54:30.450
So the Kyoto Protocol
called for Annex I countries

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:32.310
to make reductions.

00:54:32.310 --> 00:54:39.760
It was ratified by the members
of the European Union, Japan,

00:54:39.760 --> 00:54:43.980
Australia, Canada,
lots of other folks.

00:54:43.980 --> 00:54:46.620
We did not.

00:54:46.620 --> 00:54:51.720
The history of that is roughly
that President Clinton,

00:54:51.720 --> 00:54:55.530
in the run up to
those negotiations,

00:54:55.530 --> 00:54:58.410
there was a lot of noise
in the air about how

00:54:58.410 --> 00:54:59.220
this will be free.

00:54:59.220 --> 00:55:01.813
It'll be a great benefit
to the US economy.

00:55:01.813 --> 00:55:02.730
This will be fabulous.

00:55:02.730 --> 00:55:03.730
We can reduce emissions.

00:55:03.730 --> 00:55:05.100
It'll be no cost.

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:08.688
Every economist not working
for the administration stood up

00:55:08.688 --> 00:55:10.980
and said, well, it's not
going to cost that much money,

00:55:10.980 --> 00:55:13.570
but it will cost.

00:55:13.570 --> 00:55:17.170
Congress passed a resolution
95 to nothing saying,

00:55:17.170 --> 00:55:18.970
we won't ratify anything that--

00:55:18.970 --> 00:55:21.100
basically, slightly
different language--

00:55:21.100 --> 00:55:23.980
that doesn't require the
Chinese to do something now.

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:25.970
95 to nothing.

00:55:25.970 --> 00:55:28.570
So Al Gore went to Kyoto.

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:32.680
The US said, this is fabulous.

00:55:32.680 --> 00:55:33.910
We made an agreement.

00:55:33.910 --> 00:55:38.690
The treaty was not sent to
the Senate for ratification.

00:55:38.690 --> 00:55:42.820
And President George
W. Bush formally

00:55:42.820 --> 00:55:46.330
declared the horse dead
in 2001 when he said,

00:55:46.330 --> 00:55:48.470
we're not going to play.

00:55:48.470 --> 00:55:51.190
So the EU has
established-- and again,

00:55:51.190 --> 00:55:54.460
you can read the Parsons, et
al, article if you're interested

00:55:54.460 --> 00:55:55.210
in it--

00:55:55.210 --> 00:55:57.130
established an emissions
trading scheme.

00:55:57.130 --> 00:56:01.000
They did the certificates
dropped from the air that

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.100
lets you emit carbon dioxide.

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:04.840
I mean, it's not
a perfect system.

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:07.150
You'll see some glitches.

00:56:07.150 --> 00:56:09.760
But it may work.

00:56:09.760 --> 00:56:12.910
And they may actually
meet their commitments.

00:56:12.910 --> 00:56:15.740
It doesn't appear
anybody else will,

00:56:15.740 --> 00:56:18.440
even those that
ratified the treaty.

00:56:18.440 --> 00:56:20.450
Australia's walking away.

00:56:20.450 --> 00:56:23.700
I think Canada has walked away.

00:56:23.700 --> 00:56:27.230
Japan may because of
the incredible disaster

00:56:27.230 --> 00:56:33.830
they've gone through but
would not have absent it

