You're telling us that
you got to do that.

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:21.110
And you're now leaning on us.

01:10:21.110 --> 01:10:25.130
The fear isn't that
boatloads of investment

01:10:25.130 --> 01:10:27.680
will come in and
modernize their factory.

01:10:27.680 --> 01:10:30.290
The fear is that you're going
to raise the price of fuel

01:10:30.290 --> 01:10:32.150
to my poor people.

01:10:32.150 --> 01:10:35.900
A lot of these countries
subsidize fuel.

01:10:35.900 --> 01:10:39.380
And I don't want to
take the political heat

01:10:39.380 --> 01:10:45.248
from something that
restricts my ability to grow.

01:10:45.248 --> 01:10:47.040
If you're telling me
that the Europeans are

01:10:47.040 --> 01:10:49.457
going to come in and modernize
my factories, that's swell.

01:10:49.457 --> 01:10:50.670
I love it.

01:10:50.670 --> 01:10:52.650
If you're telling me
that I have to change

01:10:52.650 --> 01:10:57.600
my policies in a way that
might slow growth and keep

01:10:57.600 --> 01:11:01.690
my people poor, I'm
not real excited.

01:11:01.690 --> 01:11:06.820
And you can say
I've been talking

01:11:06.820 --> 01:11:09.700
about your grandchildren
and great-grandchildren.

01:11:09.700 --> 01:11:13.100
Well, I mean, if your
kids are starving today,

01:11:13.100 --> 01:11:15.980
that's a pretty
abstract argument.

01:11:15.980 --> 01:11:17.630
That's real abstract.

01:11:17.630 --> 01:11:26.920
So other comments, reactions,
questions, thoughts?

01:11:26.920 --> 01:11:28.015
Oh, yeah?

01:11:28.015 --> 01:11:32.710
AUDIENCE: So mostly we've been
talking about greenhouse gases.

01:11:32.710 --> 01:11:34.360
Is there any
international discussion

01:11:34.360 --> 01:11:37.570
about other like
climate-changing courses,

01:11:37.570 --> 01:11:41.718
like the black carbon or other
like aerosols, or is that not?

01:11:41.718 --> 01:11:43.510
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Not that I'm aware of.

01:11:43.510 --> 01:11:43.980
Is there some?

01:11:43.980 --> 01:11:44.290
SUSAN SOLOMON: Yes.

01:11:44.290 --> 01:11:45.720
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK.

01:11:45.720 --> 01:11:46.247
Say.

01:11:46.247 --> 01:11:47.830
SUSAN SOLOMON: Well,
I mean, the State

01:11:47.830 --> 01:11:52.770
Department, just a few weeks
ago, announced that we would--

01:11:52.770 --> 01:11:55.740
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So
they will capture you on--

01:11:55.740 --> 01:11:58.420
you didn't sign a release
form, but never mind.

01:11:58.420 --> 01:12:00.198
SUSAN SOLOMON: I release you.

01:12:00.198 --> 01:12:02.490
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: And
everyone is released out there

01:12:02.490 --> 01:12:03.282
in television land.

01:12:03.282 --> 01:12:03.960
OK.

01:12:03.960 --> 01:12:05.460
SUSAN SOLOMON: Just
a few weeks ago,

01:12:05.460 --> 01:12:08.950
the State Department announced
that we would be part of,

01:12:08.950 --> 01:12:11.100
and I guess the
leader of, an effort

01:12:11.100 --> 01:12:14.310
to try to reduce
emissions of soot

01:12:14.310 --> 01:12:17.310
and other short-lived
gases, stuff

01:12:17.310 --> 01:12:21.520
like methane and
tropospheric ozones as well.

01:12:21.520 --> 01:12:25.200
So that's a voluntary program.

01:12:25.200 --> 01:12:27.690
But there are movements
in that direction.

01:12:27.690 --> 01:12:29.790
And there is
actually quite a bit

01:12:29.790 --> 01:12:37.890
of investment in providing
very much more efficient stoves

01:12:37.890 --> 01:12:41.760
to people in very
poor countries,

01:12:41.760 --> 01:12:47.160
so that they can avoid using
things like dung and coal

01:12:47.160 --> 01:12:49.528
and stuff like that, which
generates an enormous amount

01:12:49.528 --> 01:12:50.070
of pollution.

01:12:50.070 --> 01:12:53.880
So it has both a health benefit
and an efficiency benefit.

01:12:53.880 --> 01:12:56.250
And it also cuts
carbon a little but.

01:12:56.250 --> 01:12:58.650
But realistically,
the main motivation

01:12:58.650 --> 01:13:01.380
is much more grounded in soot.

01:13:01.380 --> 01:13:05.340
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: I mean,
one reason, not the main reason

01:13:05.340 --> 01:13:08.250
necessarily, to be concerned
with black carbon emissions is

01:13:08.250 --> 01:13:10.710
the effect on the reflectivity.

01:13:10.710 --> 01:13:13.980
If you have a lot of sea
ice, ice tends to reflect.

01:13:13.980 --> 01:13:15.840
Black carbon tends to absorb.

01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:18.600
So it does matter for
climate, but it also

01:13:18.600 --> 01:13:20.190
matters when you breathe.

01:13:23.190 --> 01:13:25.930
There are lots of international
environmental treaties.

01:13:25.930 --> 01:13:28.700
Most don't have anything
to do with climate.